# Step 1: Save the Script
# -----------------------
# Open a terminal and navigate to a directory where you want to store the script.
cd ~/Desktop

# Create the script file using nano or your preferred text editor.
nano tsundere-linus.py

# Paste the Tsundere-Linus script code into the nano editor and save the file.
# (Use Ctrl + O to save and Ctrl + X to exit nano.)

# Step 2: Make the Script Executable
# ----------------------------------
# Change the file permissions to make the script executable.
chmod +x tsundere-linus.py

# Step 3: Move or Link the Script to a Directory in Your PATH
# -----------------------------------------------------------
# Option A: Move the script to /usr/local/bin to make it globally accessible.
sudo mv tsundere-linus.py /usr/local/bin/tsundere-linus

# Option B: Create a symbolic link from the script to /usr/local/bin (if you prefer to keep it in the original location).
sudo ln -s $(pwd)/tsundere-linus.py /usr/local/bin/tsundere-linus

# Step 4: Run Commands with Tsundere-Linus
# ----------------------------------------
# Use the script to execute your terminal commands. Here are a few examples:

# Example 1: Attempt to list a non-existent directory
tsundere-linus ls /nonexistentdirectory

# Example 2: Attempt to display the contents of a non-existent file
tsundere-linus cat nonexistentfile.txt

# When these commands are run, any error messages will be replaced with tsundere-style insults, such as:
# "Tsundere-Linus: Wrong syntax, baka!"

# Step 5: Customize the Script (Optional)
# ---------------------------------------
# You can customize the list of tsundere-style insults by editing the script and modifying the tsundere_insults list.
# Simply open the script in your text editor again:
nano /usr/local/bin/tsundere-linus

# Add, remove, or change the insults as you see fit, then save the changes.
